    <ol class="timeline">
        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 5000–3100 BCE: <span>Prehistoric Egypt</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Farming communities appear along the Nile, leading to the development of
                proto-kingdoms such as Naqada and Badari.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/72/Naqada_vessel.jpg" alt="Naqada pottery"
                class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item right">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 3100–2686 BCE: <span>Early Dynastic Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Narmer (possibly Menes) unifies Upper and Lower Egypt, establishes Memphis
                as the capital, and starts dynastic rule.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0e/Narmer_Palette.jpg" alt="Narmer Palette"
                class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 2686–2181 BCE: <span>Old Kingdom</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Era of pyramid building including the Great Pyramid of Giza under Pharaoh
                Khufu. Egypt is unified and stable.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e3/Kheops-Pyramid.jpg" alt="Great Pyramid"
                class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item right">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 2181–2055 BCE: <span>First Intermediate Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">A time of political fragmentation and decline following the collapse of the
                Old Kingdom, with rival dynasties in Herakleopolis and Thebes.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/11/Sarcophagus_of_Ankhtifi.jpg"
                alt="Ankhtifi tomb" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 2055–1650 BCE: <span>Middle Kingdom</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Egypt is reunited under Mentuhotep II. Art, literature, and central
                governance thrive; military expeditions expand borders.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/12/MentuhotepSeatedStatue-BritishMuseum-August19-08.jpg"
                alt="Mentuhotep II" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item right">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 1650–1550 BCE: <span>Second Intermediate Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Hyksos rulers from the Levant control northern Egypt. Horse-drawn chariots
                and new warfare tactics are introduced.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/Scarab_Hyksos_Louvre_E3246.jpg"
                alt="Hyksos scarab" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 1550–1070 BCE: <span>New Kingdom</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Egypt reaches its peak in wealth and power. Notable pharaohs include
                Hatshepsut, Akhenaten, Tutankhamun, and Ramesses II.</p>
            <img src="img/nefertiti.png" alt="Abu Simbel" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item right">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 1070–664 BCE: <span>Third Intermediate Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Egypt is divided between rival dynasties, including Libyan and Nubian
                rulers. Authority declines across the region.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/53/Tanitamon_kneeling_statue.jpg"
                alt="Nubian ruler" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">c. 664–332 BCE: <span>Late Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Brief resurgence under native rule. Persia invades Egypt twice. Egyptian
                culture remains strong despite foreign dominance.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d9/Horus_temple_Edfu_07.JPG"
                alt="Temple of Horus at Edfu" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item right">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">332–30 BCE: <span>Ptolemaic Period</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">Alexander the Great conquers Egypt. His general Ptolemy I establishes Greek
                rule. Cleopatra VII is the final ruler of this era.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fb/Cleopatra_coin_42BC.jpg"
                alt="Coin of Cleopatra" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>

        <li class="timeline__item">
            <h3 class="timeline__day">30 BCE–641 CE: <span>Roman & Byzantine Egypt</span></h3>
            <p class="timeline__day-sum">After Cleopatra’s death, Egypt becomes a Roman province. Ancient religious
                practices decline as Christianity spreads.</p>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e2/Alexandria_Roman_theatre.jpg"
                alt="Roman Theatre Alexandria" class="timeline__photo">
        </li>
    </ol>

    <script>
        // Fade-in on scroll
        const observer = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    entry.target.classList.add('visible');
                }
            });
        }, { threshold: 0.1 });

        document.querySelectorAll('.timeline__item').forEach(item => {
            observer.observe(item);
        });
    </script>
